{{Infobox Person | name = Josephus Augustinus Brentano | image = J. A. Brentano, Adriaan de Lelie, 1813, Stichting Brentano's Steun des Ouderdoms, Amstelveen.jpg | caption = J. A. Brentano by [[Adriaan de Lelie]], 1813 | birth_date = 28 August 1753 | birth_place = [[Amsterdam]] | death_date = 16 April 1821 | death_place = [[Amsterdam]] | nationality = [[Netherlands]] }} '''Josephus Augustinus Brentano''' (1753 – 1821) was a [[Netherlands|Dutch]] art collector.
Brentano was born in [[Amsterdam]] and became a merchant in trade with the [[Dutch East India Company|VOC]] and the [[Dutch West India Company|WIC]]. He was not unsuccessful and retired early in a canal mansion on the [[Herengracht]] (today nr. 544). He formed a large art cabinet there that ''competed'' with the one formed by [[Jan Gildemeester]] further down the canal. Like Gildemeester, he hired [[Adriaan de Lelie]] to portray him among his prize paintings. He started the collection to ''encourage artists in their field'', according to [[Roeland van Eynden]] and [[Adriaan van der Willigen]].<ref>[http://resources.huygens.knaw.nl/retroboeken/vaderlandsche_schilderkunst/#source=III&page=481 Brentano] in Van Eynden and Van der Willigen's ''[[Geschiedenis der Vaderlandsche Schilderkunst]]''</ref>
<gallery> File:De kunstgalerij van Josephus Augustinus Brentano Rijksmuseum SK-A-4122.jpeg|Brentano in his art cabinet File:Amsterdam - Herengracht 544 en 542.JPG|Location of his canal mansion today </gallery> Brentano died a bachelor in [[Amsterdam]] and his collection was sold to found a home for poor elderly men.
